The paper deals with two well-studied problems in theoretical computer science, namely the Hitting Set problem and the Directed Dominating Set problem (also known as Nonblocker). These problems are typically studied in the sub-fields of algorithms and complexity theory, which are covered by the arXiv categories cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.CC (Computational Complexity), cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics), cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory), and cs.CG (Computational Geometry). Given that the paper focuses on parameterized complexity and kernelization, it is likely to be classified under one or more of these categories. Among these, cs.DS and cs.CC are the most likely categories, as they are the most closely related to the topics of the paper. However, cs.DM, cs.GT, and cs.CG are also possible categories, as they are relevant to some of the techniques and concepts used in the paper.
